<body style="margin:0;padding:0;background-color:#ffffff;font-family:-apple-system,BlinkMacSystemFont,'Segoe UI',Roboto,Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;color:#27272a;">
  <div style="max-width:600px;margin:0 auto;padding:32px 20px;">
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;">Hey,</p>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;">Day 5. This is structural pricing, not benchmark numbers. Labor rates, overhead, and margins vary too much by market and shop size for made-up averages to be useful.</p>
    <h2 style="font-size:17px;color:#18181b;margin:28px 0 10px 0;">Two modes</h2>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 10px 0;"><strong>Cost-plus</strong> works when scope is variable: direct labor, materials, sub-labor, overhead recovery, and profit.</p>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 18px 0;"><strong>Flat-rate</strong> works when the task is repeatable and you know the standard time. It rewards efficiency but punishes under-scoped tasks.</p>
    <h2 style="font-size:17px;color:#18181b;margin:28px 0 10px 0;">Costs that eat margin</h2>
    <ul style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 18px 24px;padding:0;">
      <li>Truck, fuel, insurance, maintenance, and tool replacement.</li>
      <li>Licensing, bonding, continuing education, and admin time.</li>
      <li>Drive time, quotes that do not close, callbacks, and warranty work.</li>
      <li>Return trips in the first 90 days after install.</li>
    </ul>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;">A useful exercise: estimate annual non-payroll costs and true billable hours, then compare the resulting cost-per-hour to what you actually charge on jobs that feel "profitable." That is where margin leaks show up.</p>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">Day 14 is the Angi Pro email: direct, with the math to run.</p>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:20px 0 4px 0;">&mdash; NailTheQuote</p>
